ility exist at the global level that promote global social justice based on different sets of principles?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-SA 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aInternational lawxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aInternational lawxPhilosophy. 0aJustice. 0aPhilosophy (General). 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophy. 4aEuropäische Union. 4aGlobalisierung. 4aMigration. 4aMoralphilosophie. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Modern.2bisacsh  aGlobalization.  aeuropean union.  amigration.  amoral philosophy.1 aBens, Oliver, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBénassy-Quéré, Agnès, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDaniels, Detlef von, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDaniels, Detlef, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aForst, Rainer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrançois, Etienne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGerhardt, Volker, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGethmann, Carl Friedrich, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerzog, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHüttl, Reinhard F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaiser, Knut, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKamp, Georg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKreide, Regina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKumm, Mattias, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.go